EverQuest: The Movie!  <br>
 <br>
Posted on 3/31/2001<br>
 <br>
 <br>
One of the unanticipated benefits of the advances in computer games technology over the last few years is this:<br>
<br>
Before, all you could do was make ghastly video games based on computer games. Now, computer games are sufficiently complex and compelling that we can make ghastly movies based on them, instead of the other way around. With any luck, the next step in this evolution will be making truly execrable video games based on lousy movies based on video games which, to be blunt, weren't all that great to begin with.<br>
<br>
  <br>
<br>
<br>
But I have already lost my focus. Allow me to regroup. The main problem with video games based on movies is, simply, they are too divorced from their source material. Sure, we're all going to get to drool over Angelina Jolie's perfect abs when the Tomb Raider movie comes out, but that doesn't change the fact that the movie will be nothing like the gaming experience.<br>
<br>
If Tomb Raider The Movie was anything like Tomb Raider The Game, it would begin with 10 minutes of watching Lara learn how to climb on top of a box and jump over a five foot gap. And, in the middle of the movie, Lara would spend fifteen minutes going through rooms she's already been in looking for the key she missed.<br>
<br>
If Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within (coming out this year) is anything like the game series, there will be a fight where the main character summons a dragon to hit the enemy, and then summons the exact same dragon eight more times. Then, when all that is done, he will spend an hour rearranging his materia.<br>
<br>
And every so often in the Mario Brothers movie, Mario should have jumped up and smacked his head against the ceiling to see if any coins fell out.<br>
<br>
(By these standards, the best video game movie ever made was Mortal Kombat. Mortal Kombat The Game was about pairs of people beating the crap out of each other for no apparent reason. The movie was exactly the same. This makes Mortal Kombat the Citizen Kane of video game movies.)<br>
<br>
Movies based on video games have a nasty and amusing tendency to bomb. Video game fun almost always translates very poorly to something that's fun to watch, so the poor filmmakers are stuck trying to make some standard, cheesy action movie using a fixed set of characters which weren't really made up to be in a standard, cheesy action movie. But they have to keep making them, and that is why I want to be the first brave soul to suggest making (with someone else's money, of course), EverQuest: The Movie.<br>
<br>
Picture it with me. It is tempting to make it your standard Young Loser Rises To Fame story, in which Luke starts out by killing rats and beetles behind Uncle Ben's farm but eventually rises, Rocky-like, to strike down Nagafen the dragon and get a really good breastplate. But, instead, I want to be an auteur and get to the true heart of the EverQuest experience.<br>
<br>
  <br>
<br>
<br>
So the movie will open on a room. There are six mighty heroes in it. Their general demeanor strongly indicates that they have been sitting there for a long time. There's graffiti on the wall. Discarded food wrappers everywhere. They sit quietly for a while. Occasionally, someone asks, &quot;How's everyone's buffs doing?&quot;<br>
<br>
Then, suddenly, action! Out of nowhere, several monsters charge into the room! Our heroes butcher them in a vibrant, kinetic, action scene! Fireballs everywhere! And then, when the monsters are slain, one of the hobbits pushes the corpses out of the room and everyone sits down again.<br>
<br>
This wouldn't be the whole movie, of course. The adventurers would get in a shouting argument with the adventurers in the next room. Eventually, one hero will suddenly disappear, and another will appear to take his place. The lead warrior will have to fight a duel with someone named K00lDood314. And, at the climax, someone will get a really good breastplate. They'll roll dice for it.<br>
<br>
The end.<br>
<br>
So there's my proposal. I see all six adventurers being played by Angelina Jolie. It'll be like The Nutty Professor, with swords. Producers, I'll be waiting by the phone.<br>
<br>
